  <section class="hero">
   <div class="wrap">
    <h1>
     [FR]: Choking: clear the airway fast
    </h1>
    <p>
     [FR]: How to help someone who is choking — an adult, a child, or a baby — and what to do if they stop breathing. Acting in the first minutes can prevent death or brain injury. Free to read, print, and share.
    </p>
   </div>
  </section>
  <main id="main">
   <div class="wrap">
    <p class="lede">
     [FR]: Choking happens when something blocks the airway and stops air from getting to the lungs. If the person can still cough or speak, the blockage is partial — encourage them to keep coughing. If they
     <strong>
      [FR]: cannot breathe, speak, or cough,
     </strong>
     [FR]: the airway is badly blocked and you must act right away.
    </p>
    <div class="actions no-print">
     <a class="btn" href="javascript:window.print()">
      [FR]: Print this page
     </a>
     <a class="btn alt" href="choking-onepager.pdf">
      [FR]: Download printable PDF
     </a>
    </div>
    <div class="box emergency">
     <span class="tag">
      Call emergency services
     </span>
     <h3>
      [FR]: Severe choking is an emergency
     </h3>
     <p>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [FR]: Call your local emergency number (examples: 911, 112, or 999; verify locally), or have someone else call, if a person is choking and
      <strong>
       [FR]: cannot breathe, speak, cry, or cough
      </strong>
      [FR]: , is clutching their throat, is going silent or blue, or becomes unconscious. If you are alone with them, give first aid first and call as soon as you can — put the phone on speaker.
     </p>
    </div>
    <h2>
     [FR]: First, tell mild from severe
    </h2>
    <div class="two">
     <div class="box ok">
      <span class="tag ok">
       Mild — let them cough
      </span>
      <ul>
       <li>
        [FR]: Can still cough forcefully, speak, or breathe
       </li>
       <li>
        [FR]: Coughing is the most effective way to clear it
       </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
       <strong>
        [FR]: Encourage them to keep coughing.
       </strong>
       [FR]: Do not slap their back or do thrusts yet; stay with them and be ready to act if it gets worse.
      </p>
     </div>
     <div class="box emergency">
      <span class="tag">
       Severe — act now
      </span>
      <ul>
       <li>
        [FR]: Cannot breathe, speak, cry, or make sounds
       </li>
       <li>
        [FR]: Silent or very weak cough; clutching the throat
       </li>
       <li>
        [FR]: Lips or face turning blue; looking panicked
       </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
       <strong>
        [FR]: Begin first aid immediately
       </strong>
       [FR]: and get emergency help.
      </p>
     </div>
    </div>
    <h2>
     [FR]: Adult or child (over 1 year)
    </h2>
    <ol class="steps">
     <li>
      <strong>
       🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [FR]: Give up to 5 back blows.
      </strong>
      [FR]: Stand to the side and slightly behind. Support their chest with one hand and lean them well forward. With the heel of your other hand, give up to five firm blows between the shoulder blades. Check after each one to see if the blockage has cleared.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [FR]: Give up to 5 abdominal thrusts.
      </strong>
      [FR]: Stand behind them and put your arms around their waist. Make a fist just above the navel and below the ribcage; grasp it with your other hand and pull sharply inward and upward, up to five times.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [FR]: Keep alternating
      </strong>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [FR]: 5 back blows and 5 abdominal thrusts until the object comes out, the person can breathe, or they become unconscious.
     </li>
    </ol>
    <div class="box warn">
     <span class="tag warn">
      For a pregnant person or a very large person
     </span>
     <p>
      [FR]: Do not give abdominal thrusts. Instead give
      <strong>
       [FR]: chest thrusts
      </strong>
      [FR]: : place your fist on the center of the breastbone and pull straight back, sharp and firm, alternating with back blows.
     </p>
    </div>
    <h2>
     [FR]: Baby (under 1 year)
    </h2>
    <div class="box warn">
     <span class="tag warn">
      Never give a baby abdominal thrusts
     </span>
     <p>
      [FR]: Use back blows and chest thrusts only. Support the head at all times.
     </p>
    </div>
    <ol class="steps">
     <li>
      <strong>
       🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [FR]: 5 back blows.
      </strong>
      [FR]: Lay the baby face-down along your forearm with the head lower than the body, supporting the jaw and head. Give up to five firm blows between the shoulder blades with the heel of your hand.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [FR]: 5 chest thrusts.
      </strong>
      [FR]: Turn the baby face-up along your other forearm, head still lower than the body. Place two fingers on the center of the chest (lower half of the breastbone) and give up to five quick, firm thrusts.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [FR]: Keep alternating
      </strong>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [FR]: 5 back blows and 5 chest thrusts. Call emergency services if the baby does not start breathing, and continue until help arrives or the baby becomes unresponsive.
     </li>
    </ol>
    <h2>
     [FR]: If the person becomes unconscious
    </h2>
    <div class="box emergency">
     <span class="tag">
      Start CPR
     </span>
     <ol>
      <li>
       [FR]: Lower them carefully to the floor and
       <strong>
        [FR]: call emergency services now
       </strong>
       [FR]: (speaker phone) if not already done.
      </li>
      <li>
       [FR]: Begin
       <strong>
        [FR]: CPR
       </strong>
       [FR]: : chest compressions, and rescue breaths if you are trained and willing. If you are not trained, follow the dispatcher's instructions; they may guide hands-only CPR until help arrives.
      </li>
      <li>
       [FR]: Each time you open the airway to give breaths,
       <strong>
        [FR]: look in the mouth
       </strong>
       [FR]: and remove any object you can clearly see. Do not sweep blindly with your finger, which can push it deeper.
      </li>
      <li>
       [FR]: Continue until the person recovers or emergency help takes over.
      </li>
     </ol>
    </div>
    <div class="box ok">
     <span class="tag ok">
      After a severe choking episode
     </span>
     <p>
      [FR]: Anyone who needed back blows or thrusts — or who has a lasting cough, trouble swallowing, or a feeling that something is still stuck — should be checked by a medical professional, because thrusts can occasionally cause internal injury and small fragments can remain.
     </p>
    </div>
    <h2>
     [FR]: Prevent choking, especially in young children
    </h2>
    <ul>
     <li>
      [FR]: Cut food for young children into small pieces; encourage everyone to eat slowly and not talk or laugh with a full mouth.
     </li>
     <li>
      [FR]: For children under about 4, avoid or modify high-risk foods: whole grapes and cherry tomatoes (cut them up), nuts, popcorn, hard or sticky candy, chunks of meat or hot dog, and raw hard vegetables.
     </li>
     <li>
      [FR]: Keep small objects — coins, button batteries, marbles, small toy parts, deflated balloons — out of reach of babies and toddlers.
     </li>
     <li>
      [FR]: Supervise young children while they eat, and keep them seated.
     </li>
    </ul>
    <h2>
     [FR]: Sources
    </h2>
    <ul class="sources">
     <li>
      <a href="https://www.redcross.org/take-a-class">
       [FR]: American Red Cross — first aid training and resources
      </a>
      [FR]: , including conscious choking guidance.
     </li>
     <li>
      <a href="https://cpr.heart.org/en/resuscitation-science/first-aid-guidelines/first-aid">
       🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [FR]: American Heart Association (AHA) — first aid guidelines
      </a>
      [FR]: for choking and CPR.
     </li>
     <li>
      <a href="https://www.resus.org.uk/library">
       [FR]: Resuscitation Council UK — resuscitation and first-aid guidance library
      </a>
      [FR]: , including choking guidance.
     </li>
     <li>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [FR]: U.S. CDC and national child-safety guidance on choking and suffocation prevention. cdc.gov
     </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="sources">
     [FR]: Steps reflect widely taught Red Cross / Resuscitation Council first-aid sequences for lay responders. Different training bodies vary in detail — follow your local first-aid training and emergency dispatcher's instructions.
    </p>
    <p class="disclaimer">
     [FR]: This guide is general information, not medical advice, and is not a substitute for hands-on first-aid and CPR training, which is widely available and strongly recommended. In an emergency, always call your local emergency number. Reuse and reprint freely.
    </p>
   </div>
